          "body": "The verb 'pronounce' (*tame*, unclean; *taher*, clean) recurs throughout the chapter with insistent force. The priest does not merely observe a condition; he declares it. This distinction is theologically significant. A person with a skin condition is not automatically in a state of impurity until the priest makes the declaration — the community waits on the authorized verdict. Conversely, the clean verdict is not the individual's self-assessment but the priest's authorized pronouncement. Gordon Wenham (*The Book of Leviticus*, NICOT) notes that this structure prevents both self-condemnation and self-exoneration. The priest is not a healer but a mediator of holy status — functioning as a judicial representative of YHWH's standard. This anticipates the New Testament's portrayal of Jesus, who cleanses lepers by *declaration* and commands them to 'show themselves to the priests' (Luke 17:14; Matthew 8:4), both fulfilling the Levitical procedure and revealing Himself as the one who makes its verdict possible."
