        "excerpt": "Now if a man or woman has an infection on the head or on the beard, then the priest shall look at the infection, and if it appears to be deeper than the skin and there is thin yellowish hair in it, then the priest shall pronounce him unclean. (13:29-30)",
        "body": "Verses 18-44 apply the chapter's diagnostic logic to five specific presentations: lesions at a healed boil site (18-23), lesions at a burn site (24-28), scalp and beard infections (29-37), harmless white bright spots (38-39), and baldness with or without lesions (40-44). The multiplication of cases is not legal pedantry; it is pastoral precision. Every presentation a priest might encounter is addressed, so that no sufferer falls outside the protocol and no priest must improvise.\n\nThe boil-site and burn-site cases (vv. 18-28) both apply the standard diagnostic criteria — depth, hair color, spread — to secondary lesions arising after a prior wound. The law recognizes that *tsara'at* can erupt in weakened tissue; the diagnostic process is the same regardless of origin. Both cases use the same quarantine provision (seven days) when ambiguous, and the same clean or unclean verdict criteria when decisive signs are present.\n\nThe scalp cases (vv. 29-37) introduce a new diagnostic marker: yellow thin hair (*tsahov daq*, v. 30) signals scalp *tsara'at* in place of the body's white hair. The absence of black hair (v. 31) — healthy, dark hair that would indicate normal growth — is also significant. Verse 37 describes the sign of healing with equal precision: the scaly outbreak has remained unchanged AND black hair has grown in it. Black hair regrowth is the scalp's equivalent of the body's raw flesh turning white — a sign of resolution.\n\nVerses 38-44 handle two conditions that might be confused with *tsara'at*: dull-white bright spots (eczema, v. 39 — declared clean) and baldness (vv. 40-41 — declared clean categorically). The explicitness here guards against stigmatizing natural conditions. The law is careful not to extend the *tsara'at* category beyond its proper bounds. But baldness with a reddish-white sore on it (vv. 42-44) is a different matter — *tsara'at* can break out on bald skin, and the priest must look for it there too.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Neteq* (scale/scalp infection, vv. 30-37) is distinct from *tsara'at* proper in the Talmudic tradition but treated under the same diagnostic protocol here. *Tsahov* (yellow) and *daq* (thin/fine) are the scalp's diagnostic hair-markers, distinct from the body's *sear lavan* (white hair). *Galach* (shave, v. 33) — the instruction to shave around but not over the scalp lesion preserves the diagnostic area for re-examination."
